Managing flood risk through the use of design standards related to the probability or
          frequency of occurrence, rather than the broader assessment and management of
          risk;

Direct damages to structures and their contents due to water
          contact;
          and

Development (including filling) within the floodplain (particularly in floodways and
            flood storage
            areas);

Providing a certain level of
            service;
            and

Risk management decisions for projects with a relatively short time frame, such
                as construction projects as well as temporary infrastructure (such as a coffer dam
                during construction);

Understanding how flood behaviour, hazards and risks may change due to floodplain,
              catchment and climate
              changes;

Limits on the scale of development to limit impacts on the existing
            community;
            and

Location A is easy to evacuate and outside the impacts of flood function and flood
              conditions are not hazardous to
              buildings;

Location B is in a floodway and development may impact upon flood behaviour and
              the flood risk of others in the
              community;

The need to consider these additional risk factors in decision making may not be
              evident;
              and

Economic Service Life - The total period to the
          time when the asset, whilst physically able to provide a service, ceases to be the lowest
          cost option to satisfy the service requirement;

Magnitude of infrastructure – very large
            infrastructure projects are more likely to remain in place longer than smaller projects
            (e.g. bridges, dams), due to the difficulties in replacing them;

Seasonality - the seasonality can alter the
statistical likelihood of flood events occurring as some events. For instance some
catchments tend to have are prone to flooding associated with summer climates;

Climatic Variability - Various weather patterns such
as El Niño influence the likelihood of flooding. El Niño events have a life-cycle during
which the impacts vary, both in terms of spatial extent and timing;

The Design Life Level aims to achieve a desired probability of exceedance (or risk
            of failure) during the Design Service Life. This method is a SLEP approach (Section 4);
